Loops
Many programs require repeated execution of code, sometimes for a variable number of times. Rather than writing the same code multiple times, it is better to use a loop.
for loop
A for loop follows the following syntax:
for (; ; ) {
    # statements to loop
}

The  expression initializes the loop and is executed once when the loop begins. After each iteration of the loop, the  expression is executed and then the  condition is checked. When the  condition is false, the loop terminates.
If the  condition evaluates to false when the loop begins, the contents of a for loop will not be run.
$factorial = 1;
# The loop below runs 4 times
for ($i = 5; $i > 1; $i--) {
    $factorial *= $i;
}
# $factorial holds 5 * 4 * 3 * 2 = 5! = 120

